<div class="container">
    <div class="">


        <h1 class="bg-danger">Pinot Noir</h1>
        <p>The world's most popular light-bodied red is loved for its red fruit and spice flavors that are accentuated by a long, smooth, soft-tannin finish.</p>

    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>PRIMARY FLAVORS</h3>
        <img src="~/Content/img/img grapes/pinot-flavours.png" />
    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>HANDLING</h3>
        <img src="~/Content/img/img grapes/pinot-handling.png" />
    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>FOOD PAIRING</h3>
        <p> A very versatile food pairing wine given it's higher high acidity and lower tannin. Pinot Noir pairs particularly well with duck, chicken, pork and mushrooms.</p>
    </div>


</div>

<div class="container">
    <div class="">


        <h1 class="bg-danger">Merlot</h1>
        <p>
            Merlot is loved for it's boisterous black cherry flavors, supple tannins, and chocolatey finish. On the high end, it's often mistaken with Cabernet Sauvignon and commonly blended with it.

        </p>

    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>PRIMARY FLAVORS</h3>
        <img src="~/Content/img/img grapes/merlot-flavour.png" />
    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>HANDLING</h3>
        <img src="~/Content/img/img grapes/merlot-handling.png" />
    </div>

    <div>
        <h3>FOOD PAIRING</h3>
        <p> Merlot tastes great alongside roasted foods like pork shoulder, roasted mushrooms or braised short ribs. Try complementing the fruit notes with chimichurri sauce.</p>
    </div>


</div>

